  "prompt": "What could cause your period to be 14 days late other than pregnancy?",
  "response": "A missed or significantly late period can be influenced by a variety of factors aside from pregnancy. Here are some possible reasons:\n\n1. **Stress:** High levels of physical or emotional stress can disrupt the hormonal balance necessary for regular menstrual cycles.\n\n2. **Weight Changes:**\n   - **Weight Gain or Loss:** Significant changes in body weight can affect hormone production and lead to irregular periods.\n   - **Eating Disorders:** Conditions like anorexia or bulimia can disrupt normal menstrual cycles.\n\n3. **Excessive Exercise:** Intense physical activity, especially when combined with low body fat, can interfere with hormonal regulation and delay menstruation.\n\n4. **Hormonal Imbalances:**\n   - **Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS):** This condition affects hormone levels, leading to irregular or missed periods.\n   - **Thyroid Disorders:** Both hypothyroidism and hyperthyroidism can disrupt menstrual cycles.\n   - **Hyperprolactinemia:** Elevated levels of prolactin can interfere with ovulation.\n\n5. **Perimenopause:** The transitional period before menopause can cause irregular menstrual cycles, including missed periods.\n\n6. **Medications:**\n   - **Birth Control:** Starting, stopping, or changing contraceptive methods can affect your menstrual cycle.\n   - **Antidepressants and Antipsychotics:** Some medications can influence hormone levels and menstrual regularity.\n\n7. **Chronic Conditions:** Diseases such as diabetes, celiac disease, or autoimmune disorders can impact menstrual cycles.\n\n8. **Illness or Surgery:** Acute or chronic illnesses, as well as surgical procedures, can temporarily disrupt menstrual patterns.\n\n9. **Travel or Changes in Routine:** Significant changes in daily schedules, especially those involving travel across time zones, can affect your menstrual cycle.\n\n10. **Breastfeeding:** Prolactin, the hormone responsible for milk production, can suppress ovulation and delay menstruation.\n\n11. **Environmental Factors:** Exposure to certain environmental toxins or extreme temperatures may impact hormonal balance.\n\n12. **Genetic Factors:** Some women naturally have longer or irregular menstrual cycles due to their genetic makeup.\n\nIf your period is consistently irregular or you experience other symptoms, it's advisable to consult a healthcare professional. They can help determine the underlying cause and recommend appropriate treatment or lifestyle adjustments.",
